  "doc_id": "15382",
  "text": "Solution. \"Dresden protocol\" [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] is suitable for corneal thickness (CT) over 400 m. However, in many advanced keratoconus patients, CT is less than 400 m. Kymionis et al. [CITATION_3] applied CXL with \"Dresden protocol\" [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] to thin cornea (range 340 ± 399 m) and found a significant endothelial cell count loss. But no other signs of intraocular toxicity (lens-retina) were noted during the follow-up. Hafezi and associates [CITATION_6] proposed using hypoosmolar riboflavin solution (0.1% riboflavin in 0.9% saline instead of dextran) as an alternative treatment protocol. But Hafezi et al. study did not include endothelial cell count measurements which could verify the safety of the technique. Gu et al. [CITATION_7] investigated the safety and efficacy of using hypoosmolar riboflavin solution (0.1%) and UVA cross-linking for the treatment of keratoconus with the thin cornea (mean thinnest CT was 413.9 ± 12.4 m and 381.1 ± 7.3 m with and without epithelium). During a 12-month follow-up, the mean keratometric ( ) value improved from 58.7 ± 3.5 diopters (D) to 57.7 ± 4.9 D ( = 0.611), and the endothelial cell density (ECD) was 2731.4 ± 191.8 cells/mm 2 before treatment and decreased to 2722.5 ± 211.5 cells/mm 2 ( = 0.208) at 6 months after treatment and returned to 2733.4 ± 222.6 cells/mm 2 ( = 0.327) at 12 months. The ECD counts before and 6-and 12-month values after treatment showed no significant change (all with > 0.05). Gu et al. proved that in patients with thin corneas (minimum CT less than 400 m after epithelial removal), hypoosmolar riboflavin solution should be an alternative protocol for CXL. However, Hafezi [CITATION_8] reported a failure case by using hypoosmolar riboflavin solution in an extremely thin cornea (268 m without epithelial) and suggested that CXL could only be administrated in cases when stromal thickness is over 330 m before swelling with hypoosmolar riboflavin solution.",
